**'Saqaliya' is Bang-E-Dara Part 2, chapter 21.** The historical lament Iqbal voices is the extinction of Muslim/Arab civilization's presence in Sicily. He weeps before "the grave of Hejazi civilization" — a people who once shook imperial courts, freed humanity from superstition, and whose Takbir rang across the Mediterranean. Sicily was their cultural cradle; now only ruins remain. Iqbal places this grief within a lineage of Islamic historical mourning: Hafiz over Baghdad, Dagh over Delhi (Jahanabad), Ibn Badrun over Granada — and now Iqbal himself, self-described as "the dust of that caravan for which you [Sicily] were the destination," carrying the island's lament back to Hindustan.
